'''Jorge R. Acosta''' (1904–5 March 1975) was a [[Mexico|Mexican]] [[archaeologist]] who worked on numerous major [[archaeological site]]s in [[Mesoamerica]], including [[Chichen Itza]], [[Teotihuacán]], [[Oaxaca]], [[Palenque]], [[Monte Albán]] and [[Tula (Mesoamerican site)|Tula]]. His excavations at Tula were the first to prove that the ruins there were that of the legendary city of [[Tollan]], the capital of the [[Toltec]] state. He also greatly influenced the practice of cultural [[conservation-restoration|conservation]] in Mexico.<ref name="Murray encyclopedia">{{cite encyclopedia |last=Cobean |first=Roberto |last2=Flores |first2=Alba Guadalupe Mastache |editor=Tim Murray |encyclopedia=Encyclopedia of Archaeology: History and Discoveries |title=Acosta, Jorge R. |url=http://www.credoreference.com/entry/abcarch/brodar_srecko |accessdate=8 November 2010 |year=2001 |publisher=ABC-CLIO |location=Santa Barbara, CA }}</ref>

